Now let me understand the approach better. The key question is: in the `visitDocument` method, how do we check if a POM is the root/parent POM? We can use `getResolutionResult()`. If `getResolutionResult().getParent() == null` OR `!getResolutionResult().parentPomIsProjectPom()`, then this is the root POM.

Wait, but in `visitDocument`, we haven't yet visited the scm tag. Let me look at how `getResolutionResult()` works within the visitor. It uses `getCursor().getPath(Xml.Document.class::isInstance)`. In `visitDocument`, we're at the document level, so `getResolutionResult()` should work.

However, looking at `parentPomIsProjectPom()`:
```java
public boolean parentPomIsProjectPom() {
    if (getParent() == null) {
        return false;
    }
    ResolvedGroupArtifactVersion parentGav = getParent().getPom().getGav();
    return getProjectPoms().values().stream()
            .map(Pom::getGav)
            .anyMatch(gav -> gav.equals(parentGav));
}
```

If `getParent() == null`, it returns `false` — which means "the parent is NOT a project POM" (i.e., this IS the root POM). Good.

So the logic should be: when `addIfMissing` is true and the document doesn't have an `<scm>` tag, only add it if `!getResolutionResult().parentPomIsProjectPom()` — meaning this is the root POM (no parent in the project).

